An iconic image, the Slim Aarons photograph known as 'Poolside Gossip' is this year marking its 50th anniversary. Taken in January 1970 in Palm Springs, California, it came to define an image of mid-century modernism. Scroll through to enjoy original ephemera from Slim's own archive, housed at the @gettyarchive in London.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
The Poolside Gossip story begins with the 1946 design of the house by architect Richard Neutra, commissioned by businessman and philanthropist Edgar J. Kaufmann.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
On assignment for Holiday magazine, when Slim visited 'The Kaufmann House' in 1970, it belonged to art dealer Joseph Linsk and cultural patron Nelda Linsk. It would make the perfect backdrop to promote Palm Springs as a winter vacation destination.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Part of the same New York circle, Slim phoned Nelda to arrange the shoot and asked her to invite some friends along. A seemingly trivial request, Nelda‚Äôs friends became the life-blood of Poolside Gossip. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Lita Baron, the actress and singer, cuts a glamorous figure, walking down alongside the pool. Model Helen Dzo Dzo appears perfectly poised with lacquered hair and dressed in white lace, sat with Nelda Linsk in sunshine yellow.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
The photoshoot took just an hour and a half, everyone taking care of their own make-up and wardrobe. Slim just took his tripod and camera along, and captured a brilliantly colourful series of photographs. One of the shots was used in a double-page spread, shown here, and the series is now regarded as Slim‚Äôs signature work.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
The Poolside Gossip story is being celebrated by the @gettyimagesgallery throughout 2020. This weekend sees a return to the home of Poolside Gossip, with a special event in Palm Springs as part of @modernism_week.  @gracehomefurnishings will be hosting an evening with Nelda Linsk herself, with cocktails, a unique photo op and of course, plenty of gossip.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†Follow our bio link for more gallery news.‚†Ä

‚ÄúOften such talent abides by rules set by others, but Adger‚Äôs individualism sets him apart, simply because he follows his own convictions. His photographs go far as imagery can go without actually speaking.‚Äù‚†Ä
Gordon Parks on fellow photographer Adger Cowans, whose lyrical images always present more than the sum of their parts. Also an abstract expressionist painter, Cowan‚Äô sensitivity to form, texture & contrast creates lingering moods beyond what‚Äôs happening in front of the lens. Street scenes appear other-worldly, portraits reveal hidden qualities, while incidental details ‚Äì a breaking wave, hanging laundry ‚Äì become captivating dramas. ‚†Ä
First encountering the medium through his family‚Äôs Kodak Box Brownie cameras in the 1940s, Cowans served in the US Navy as a photographer, after studying at Ohio University & the Schools of Motion Picture & Visual Arts in New York.‚†Ä
Apprenticed under Parks at LIFE magazine & fashion photographer Henri Clarke, the former musician joined the African American, Harlem-based photo collective ‚ÄòKamoinge‚Äô during the 1960s. In line with the group‚Äôs ethos, Cowans was producing nuanced, differentiated representation of black lives in America as part of his wider documentary practice. ‚†Ä
Also shooting Hollywood portraiture, on set movie stills & fine art photography, his work has been exhibited in museums across the States. ‚†Ä
Across all genres, Cowans‚Äô images make visible the human complexity & emotion that can transform any given moment: ‚ÄúYou take a picture with your heart and not with your eyes. The eyes see what the heart feels."‚†Ä
Scroll through our gallery for: Harlem snow (1961); Mick Jagger (1968); Manhattan laundry (1990); director Spike Lee and cinematographer Ernest R. Dickerson on the set of 'School Daze' (1988); a New York skyscape (1975); condensation sketches in Ohio (1974), and civil rights activist Betty Shabazz, at the funeral of her husband, Malcolm X (1965).‚†Ä
@gettyarchive are profiling master photographers from our collections each week throughout US Black History Month.‚†Ä
üì∑: Adger Cowans/Getty Images | #gettyarchive‚†Ä

Originally established in 1879 to commemorate the birth of George Washington on 22nd February, 1732, what is now popularly known as Presidents' Day was designated as the third Monday of the month in 1971, when the Uniform Monday Holiday Act came into effect. ‚Å†
The standardization of federal holiday observance allowed workers to enjoy three day weekends, which discouraged absenteeism and boosted retail sales.‚Å†
With Abraham Lincoln's birthday falling on the 12th February, the relocated holiday date offered an opportunity to honour both US presidents, a suggestion not readily accepted but soon jumped upon. ‚Å†
The renaming of Washington's Birthday to President's Day has taken place unofficially and gradually, while celebrations are variously staged for both men, along with other American luminaries. Arkansas today marks the life and achievements of Daisy Bates - take a look over @gettyarchive for more on the civil rights activist.‚Å†

In a career that began with a $7.50 Voigtl√§nder Brillant camera bought in a pawnshop, Gordon Parks was, above all, a storyteller. 
Self-taught, his work is responsive and exploratory, famously liberating the static model in his fashion photography, to create pictures that suggest movement and character.
Parks began his career in earnest at the Farm Security Administration in the early 1940s. A New Deal government agency, established in response to the Great Depression, its photography department had a profound influence on documentary image-making and agency in the US.
It is while training at the FSA that Parks produced one of his most significant images ‚Äì take a look over @gettyarchive to learn more.
Having previously worked at the War Office of Information and freelanced at Vogue, Parks became the first African American staff photographer at LIFE magazine in 1948.
Using his camera like a pen, lucidity informs Parks‚Äô many essays across documentary, sports, fashion and entertainment, outlining the broader message while individuating each story with subtle details and original compositions.¬†
Assignments like ‚ÄòThe White Man‚Äôs Day is Almost Over‚Äô, ‚ÄòThe Restraints: Open and Hidden‚Äô and ‚ÄòA Harlem Family‚Äô challenged prejudice, and exposed the social issues of racial segregation and poverty to millions of readers through the pages of the American weekly.
‚ÄúThe camera is my weapon against the things I dislike about the universe‚Äù Parks once said, ‚Äúand how I show the beautiful things in the universe.‚Äù
Parks is also remembered as a prolific writer, an exhibited artist, composer, and as Hollywood‚Äôs first major black director ‚Äì 1971‚Äôs ‚ÄòShaft‚Äô being his biggest hit.
We‚Äôll be profiling master photographers from the¬†@gettyarchive collections each week throughout US Black History Month.
üì∑: Gordon Parks/ The LIFE Images Collection via Getty Images

This week saw 75,000 new historical images from the LIFE Picture Collection released to gettyimages.com.‚Å†
Representing one of the greatest bodies of 20th century photojournalism, @gettyarchive have been proud to partner with the @life magazine archives since 2003, building an exclusive online resource of one million images. This new burst anticipates another 400,000 rarely seen pictures to follow over the next five years.‚Å†
With work from the LIFE portfolio of masters including Ralph Crane, Fritz Goro, Nina Leen, Hansel Mieth, Ralph Morse, George Silk and W. Eugene Smith, visit today's @gettyarchive story or our bio link to explore life through a lens. ‚Å†

Ball games, weddings, picnics and dances. Marches, arrests, concerts and parades. From high drama to the extraordinary everyday, Pittsburgh photographer Charles ‚ÄúTeenie‚Äù Harris committed it all to posterity.
Born in 1908, Harris captured the lives of his own community across five decades, producing 80,000 negatives that today form a unique social document of urban life in America. Spending most of his working life at the Pittsburgh Courier, the seminal African American newspaper, Harris left a legacy of slow, invested photography that is rare in the more restless photojournalism of his peers. Treading the same beat with the city as his backdrop, it is the people that form the sense of place, with Harris and his camera allocating the same historical space to the bus driver as to the prize fighter.
In the context of WWII and the subsequent Civil Rights Movement, this great body of work restores the lived experience to the historic moment. A nuanced representation of 1930s ‚Äì70s African American life in the North-East, here is a community of individuals existing alongside and beyond the narrative of struggle.
Scroll through to see a handful of images from the Teenie Harris archive, now under the guardianship of the Carnegie Museum of Art, or explore the collection at ‚Ä™gettyimages.com‚Ä¨.
Nicknamed ‚ÄúOne Shot‚Äù for his ability to get the picture first time, Harris can be seen with his camera in the final slide.
We‚Äôll be profiling master photographers from the @gettyarchive collections each Thursday throughout US Black History Month.
üì∑: Charles 'Teenie' Harris/Carnegie Museum of Art/Getty Images
